691- with a neat diagram explain the 7-celled , 8-nucleate nature of the female what are chasmogamous flowers ?
692- can cross-pollination occur in cleistogamous flowers ?
693- give reasons for your answer .
694- mention two strategies evolved to prevent self-pollination in flowers .
695- what is self-incompatibility ?
696- why does self-pollination not lead to seed formation in self-incompatible species ?
697- what is bagging technique ?
698- how is it useful in a plant breeding what is triple fusion ?
699- where and how does it take place ?
700- name the nuclei involved in triple fusion .
701- why do you think the zygote is dormant for sometime in a fertilised differentiate between: what is meant by emasculation ?
702- when and why does a plant breeder employ this technique ?
703- if one can induce parthenocarpy through the application of growth substances , which fruits would you select to induce parthenocarpy and why ?
704- explain the role of tapetum in the formation of pollen-grain wall .
705- what is apomixis and what is its importance ?
706- as you are aware , humans are sexually reproducing and viviparous .
707- the reproductive events in humans include formation of gametes (gametogenesis) , i.e. , sperms in males and ovum in females , transfer of sperms into the female genital tract (insemination) and fusion of male and female gametes (fertilisation) leading to formation of zygote .
708- this is followed by formation and development of blastocyst and its attachment to the uterine wall (implantation) , embryonic development (gestation) and delivery of the baby (parturition) .
709- you have learnt that these reproductive events occur after puberty .
710- there are remarkable differences between the reproductive events in the male and in the female , for example , sperm formation continues even in old men , but formation of ovum ceases in women around the age of fifty years .
711- let us examine the male and female reproductive systems in human .
712- the male reproductive system is located in the pelvis region accessory ducts , glands and the external genitalia .
713- the testes are situated outside the abdominal cavity within a pouch called scrotum .
714- the scrotum helps in maintaining the low temperature of the testes (2–2.5 o c lower than the normal internal body temperature) necessary for spermatogenesis .
715- in adults , each testis is oval in shape , with a length of about 4 to 5 cm and a width of about 2 to 3 cm .
716- the testis is covered by a dense covering .
717- each testis has about 250 compartments each lobule contains one to three highly coiled seminiferous tubules in which sperms are produced .
718- each seminiferous tubule is lined on its inside by two types of cells called male germ cells (spermatogonia) and sertoli cells undergo meiotic divisions finally leading to sperm formation , while sertoli cells provide nutrition to the germ cells .
719- the regions outside the seminiferous tubules called interstitial spaces , contain small blood vessels and interstitial cells or leydig cells (figure 3.2) .
720- leydig cells synthesise and secrete testicular hormones called androgens .
721- other immunologically competent cells are also present .
722- showing reproductive system (part of testis is open to show inner details) the male sex accessory ducts include rete testis , vasa efferentia , epididymis and vas deferens (figure 3.1b) .
723- the seminiferous tubules of the testis open into the vasa efferentia through rete testis .
724- the vasa efferentia leave the testis and open into epididymis located along the posterior surface of each testis .
725- the epididymis leads to vas deferens that ascends to the abdomen and loops over the urinary bladder .
726- it receives a duct from seminal vesicle and opens into urethra as the ejaculatory duct (figure 3.1a) .
727- these ducts store and transport the sperms from the testis to the outside through urethra .
728- the urethra originates from the urinary bladder and extends through the penis to its external opening called urethral meatus .
729- the penis is the male external genitalia (figure 3.1a , b) .
730- it is made up of special tissue that helps in erection of the penis to facilitate insemination .
731- the enlarged end of penis called the glans penis is covered by a loose fold of skin called foreskin .
732- the male accessory glands (figure 3.1a , b) include paired seminal vesicles , a prostate and paired bulbourethral glands .
733- secretions of these glands constitute the seminal plasma which is rich in fructose , calcium and certain enzymes .
734- the secretions of bulbourethral glands also helps in the lubrication of the penis .
735- the female reproductive system consists of a pair of ovaries alongwith a pair of oviducts , uterus , cervix , vagina and the external genitalia located in pelvic region (figure 3.3a) .
736- these parts of the system alongwith a pair of the mammary glands are integrated structurally and functionally to support the processes of ovulation , fertilisation , pregnancy , birth and child care .
737- ovaries are the primary female sex organs that produce the female gamete (ovum) and several steroid hormones (ovarian hormones) .
738- the ovaries are located one on each side of the lower abdomen the pelvic wall and uterus by ligaments .
739- each ovary is covered by a thin epithelium which encloses the ovarian stroma .
740- the stroma is divided into two zones – a peripheral cortex and an inner medulla .
741- reproductive system the oviducts (fallopian tubes) , uterus and vagina constitute the female accessory ducts .
742- each fallopian tube is about 10-12 cm long and extends from the periphery of each ovary to the uterus (figure 3.3b) , the part closer to the ovary is the funnel-shaped infundibulum .
743- the edges of the infundibulum possess finger-like projections called fimbriae , which help in collection of the ovum after ovulation .
744- the infundibulum leads to a wider part of the oviduct called ampulla .
745- the last part of the oviduct , isthmus has a narrow lumen and it joins the uterus .
746- the uterus is single and it is also called womb .
747- the shape of the uterus is like an inverted pear .
748- it is supported by ligaments attached to the pelvic wall .
749- the uterus opens into vagina through a narrow cervix .
750- the cavity of the cervix is called cervical canal (figure 3.3b ) which alongwith vagina forms the birth canal .
751- the wall of the uterus has three layers of tissue .
752- the external thin membranous perimetrium , middle thick layer of smooth muscle , myometrium and inner glandular layer called endometrium that lines the uterine cavity .
753- the endometrium undergoes cyclical changes during menstrual cycle while the myometrium exhibits strong contraction during delivery of the baby .
754- the female external genitalia include mons pubis , labia majora , labia minora , hymen and clitoris (figure 3.3a) .
755- mons pubis is a cushion of fatty tissue covered by skin and pubic hair .
756- the labia majora are fleshy folds of tissue , which extend down from the mons pubis and surround the vaginal opening .
757- the labia minora are paired folds of tissue under the labia majora .
758- the opening of the vagina is often covered partially by a membrane called hymen .
759- the clitoris is a tiny finger-like structure which lies at the upper junction of the two labia minora above the urethral opening .
760- the hymen is often torn during the first coitus (intercourse) .
761- however , it can also be broken by a sudden fall or jolt , insertion of a vaginal tampon , active participation in some sports like horseback riding , cycling , etc .
762- in some women the hymen persists even after coitus .
763- in fact , the presence or absence of hymen is not a reliable indicator of virginity or sexual experience .
764- a functional mammary gland is characteristic of all female mammals .
765- the mammary glands are paired structures (breasts) that contain glandular tissue and variable amount of fat .
766- the glandular tissue of each breast is divided into 15-20 mammary lobes containing clusters of cells called alveoli (figure 3.4) .
767- the cells of alveoli secrete milk , which is stored in the cavities (lumens) of alveoli .
768- the alveoli open into mammary tubules .
769- the tubules of each lobe join to form a mammary duct .
770- several mammary ducts join to form a wider mammary ampulla which is connected to lactiferous duct through which milk is sucked out .
771- the primary sex organs – the testis in the males and the ovaries in the females – produce gametes , i.e , sperms and ovum , respectively , by the process called gametogenesis .
772- in testis , the immature male germ cells (spermatogonia) produce sperms by spermatogenesis that begins at puberty .
773- the spermatogonia (sing .
774- spermatogonium) present on the inside wall of seminiferous tubules multiply by mitotic division and increase in numbers .
775- each spermatogonium is diploid and contains 46 chromosomes .
776- some of the spermatogonia called primary spermatocytes periodically undergo meiosis .
777- a primary spermatocyte completes the first meiotic division (reduction division) leading to formation of two equal , haploid cells called secondary spermatocytes , which have only 23 chromosomes each .
778- the secondary spermatocytes undergo the second meiotic division to produce four equal , haploid spermatids (figure 3.5) .
779- what would be the number of chromosome in the spermatids ?
780- the spermatids are transformed into spermatozoa (sperms) by the process called spermiogenesis .
781- after spermiogenesis , sperm heads become embedded in the sertoli cells , and are finally released from the seminiferous tubules by the process called spermiation .
782- spermatogenesis starts at the age of puberty due to significant increase in the secretion of gonadotropin releasing hormone (gnrh) .
783- this , if you recall , is a hypothalamic hormone .
784- the increased levels of gnrh then acts at the anterior pituitary gland and stimulates secretion of two gonadotropins – luteinising hormone (lh) and follicle stimulating hormone (fsh) .
785- lh acts at the leydig cells and stimulates synthesis and secretion of androgens .
786- androgens , in turn , stimulate the process of spermatogenesis .
787- fsh acts on the sertoli cells and stimulates seminiferous tubule (enlarged) secretion of some factors which help in the process of spermiogenesis .
788- let us examine the structure of a sperm .
789- it is a microscopic structure composed of a head , neck , a middle piece and a tail (figure 3.6) .
790- a plasma membrane envelops the whole body of sperm .
791- the sperm head contains an elongated haploid nucleus , the anterior portion of which is covered by a cap-like structure , acrosome .
792- the acrosome is filled with enzymes that help fertilisation of the ovum .
793- the middle piece possesses numerous mitochondria , which produce energy for the movement of tail that facilitate sperm motility essential for fertilisation .
794- the human male ejaculates about 200 to 300 million sperms during a coitus of which , for normal fertility , at least 60 per cent sperms must have normal shape and size and at least 40 per cent of them must show vigorous sperms released from the seminiferous tubules , are transported by the accessory ducts .
795- secretions of epididymis , vas deferens , seminal vesicle and prostate are essential for maturation and motility of sperms .
796- the seminal plasma along with the sperms constitute the semen .
797- the functions of male sex accessory ducts and glands are maintained by the testicular hormones (androgens) .
798- the process of formation of a mature female gamete is called oogenesis which is markedly different from spermatogenesis .
799- oogenesis is initiated during the embryonic development stage when a couple of million gamete mother cells (oogonia) are formed within each fetal ovary ;
800- no more oogonia are formed and added after birth .
801- these cells start division and enter into prophase-i of the meiotic division and get temporarily arrested at that stage , called primary oocytes .
802- each primary oocyte then gets surrounded by a layer of granulosa cells and is called the primary follicle (figure 3.7) .
803- a large number of these follicles degenerate during the phase from birth to puberty .
804- therefore , at puberty only 60,000-80,000 primary follicles are left in each ovary .
805- the primary follicles get surrounded by more layers of granulosa cells and a new theca and are called secondary follicles .
806- the secondary follicle soon transforms into a tertiary follicle which is characterised by a fluid filled cavity called antrum .
807- the theca layer is organised into an inner theca interna and an outer theca externa .
808- it is important to draw your attention that it is at this stage that the primary oocyte within the tertiary follicle grows in size and completes its first meiotic division .
809- it is an unequal division resulting in the formation of a large haploid secondary oocyte and a tiny first polar body (figure 3.8b) .
810- the secondary oocyte retains bulk of the nutrient rich cytoplasm of the primary oocyte .
811- can you think of any advantage for this ?
812- does the first polar body born out of first meiotic division divide further or degenerate ?
813- at present we are not very certain about this .
814- the tertiary follicle further changes into the mature follicle or graafian follicle (figure 3.7) .
815- the secondary oocyte forms a new membrane called zona pellucida surrounding it .
816- the graafian follicle now ruptures to release the secondary oocyte (ovum) from the ovary by the process called ovulation .
817- can you identify major differences between spermatogenesis and oogenesis ?
818- a diagrammatic representation of spermatogenesis and oogenesis is given below (figure 3.8) .
819- the reproductive cycle in the female primates (e.g .
820- monkeys , apes and human beings) is called menstrual cycle .
821- the first menstruation begins at puberty and is called menarche .
822- in human females , menstruation is repeated at an average interval of about 28/29 days , and the cycle of events starting from one menstruation till the next one is called the menstrual cycle .
823- one ovum is released (ovulation) during the middle of each menstrual cycle .
824- the major events of the menstrual cycle are shown in figure 3.9 .
825- the cycle starts with the menstrual phase , when menstrual flow occurs and it lasts for 3-5 days .
826- the menstrual flow results due to breakdown of endometrial lining of the uterus and its blood vessels which forms liquid that comes out through vagina .
827- menstruation only occurs if the released ovum is not fertilised .
828- lack of menstruation may be indicative of pregnancy .
829- however , it may also be caused due to some other underlying causes like stress , poor health etc .
830- the menstrual phase is followed by the follicular phase .
831- during this phase , the primary follicles in the ovary grow to become a fully mature graafian follicle and simultaneously the endometrium of uterus regenerates through proliferation .
832- these changes in the ovary and the uterus are induced by changes in the levels of pituitary and ovarian hormones (figure 3.9) .
833- the secretion of gonadotropins (lh and fsh) increases gradually during the follicular phase , and stimulates follicular development as well as secretion of estrogens by the growing follicles .
834- both lh and fsh attain a peak level in the middle of cycle (about 14 th day) .
835- rapid secretion of lh leading to its maximum level during the mid-cycle called lh surge induces rupture of graafian follicle and thereby the release of ovum (ovulation) .
836- the ovulation (ovulatory phase) is followed by the luteal phase during which the remaining parts of the graafian follicle transform as the corpus luteum (figure 3.9) .
837- the corpus luteum secretes large amounts of progesterone which is essential for maintenance of the endometrium .
838- such an endometrium is necessary for implantation of the fertilised ovum and other events of pregnancy .
839- during pregnancy all events of the menstrual cycle stop and there is no menstruation .
840- in the absence of fertilisation , the corpus luteum degenerates .
841- this causes disintegration of the endometrium leading to menstruation , marking a new cycle .
842- in human beings , menstrual cycles ceases around 50 years of age ;
843- that is termed as menopause .
844- cyclic menstruation is an indicator of normal reproductive phase and extends between menarche and menopause .
845- during copulation (coitus) semen is released by the penis into the vagina (insemination) .
846- the motile sperms swim rapidly , pass through the cervix , enter into the uterus and finally reach the ampullary region of the fallopian tube (figure 3.11b) .
847- the ovum released by the ovary is also transported to the ampullary region where fertilisation takes place .
848- fertilisation can only occur if the ovum and sperms are transported simultaneously to the ampullary region .
849- this is the reason why not all copulations lead to fertilisation and the process of fusion of a sperm with an ovum is called fertilisation .
850- during fertilisation , a sperm comes in contact with the zona pellucida layer of the ovum (figure 3.10 ) and induces changes in the membrane that block the entry of additional sperms .
851- thus , it ensures that only one sperm can fertilise an ovum .
852- the secretions of the acrosome help the sperm enter into the cytoplasm of the ovum through the zona pellucida and the plasma membrane .
853- this induces the completion of the meiotic division of the secondary oocyte .
854- the second meiotic division is also unequal and results in the formation of a second polar body and a haploid ovum (ootid) .
855- soon the haploid nucleus of the sperms and that of the ovum fuse together to form a diploid zygote .
856- how many chromosomes will be there in the zygote ?
857- one has to remember that the sex of the baby has been decided at this stage itself .
858- let us see how ?
859- as you know the chromosome pattern in the human female is xx and that in the male is xy .
860- therefore , all the haploid gametes produced by the female (ova) have the sex chromosome x whereas in the male gametes (sperms) the sex chromosome could be either x or y , hence , 50 per cent of sperms carry the x chromosome while the other 50 per cent carry the y .
861- after fusion of the male and female gametes the zygote would carry either xx or xy depending on whether the sperm carrying x or y fertilised the ovum .
862- the zygote carrying xx would develop into a female baby and xy would form a male (you will learn more about the chromosomal patterns in chapter 5) .
863- that is why , scientifically it is correct to say that the sex of the baby is determined by the father and not by the mother !
864- the mitotic division starts as the zygote moves through the isthmus of the oviduct called cleavage towards the uterus (figure 3.11 ) and forms 2 , 4 , 8 , 16 daughter cells called blastomeres .
865- the embryo with 8 to 16 blastomeres is called a morula (figure 3.11e) .
866- the morula continues to divide and transforms into blastocyst (figure 3.11g ) as it moves further into the uterus .
867- the blastomeres in the blastocyst are arranged into an outer layer called trophoblast and an inner group of cells attached to trophoblast called the inner cell mass .
868- the trophoblast layer then gets attached to the endometrium and the inner cell mass gets differentiated as the embryo .
869- after attachment , the uterine cells divide rapidly and covers the blastocyst .
870- as a result , the blastocyst becomes embedded in the endometrium of the uterus (figure 3.11h) .
871- this is called implantation and it leads to pregnancy .
872- after implantation , finger-like projections appear on the trophoblast called chorionic villi which are surrounded by the uterine tissue and maternal blood .
873- the chorionic villi and uterine tissue become interdigitated with each other and jointly form a structural and functional unit between developing embryo (foetus) and maternal body called placenta (figure 3.12) .
874- the placenta facilitate the supply of oxygen and nutrients to the embryo and also removal of carbon dioxide and excretory/waste materials produced by the embryo .
875- the placenta is connected to the embryo through an umbilical cord which helps in the transport of substances to and from the embryo .
876- placenta also acts as an endocrine tissue and produces several hormones like human chorionic gonadotropin (hcg) , human placental lactogen (hpl) , estrogens , progestogens , etc .
877- in the later phase of pregnancy , a hormone called relaxin is also secreted by the ovary .
878- let us remember that hcg , hpl and relaxin are produced in women only during pregnancy .
879- in addition , during pregnancy the levels of other hormones like estrogens , progestogens , cortisol , prolactin , thyroxine , etc. , are increased several- folds in the maternal blood .
880- increased production of these hormones is essential for supporting the fetal growth , metabolic changes in the mother and maintenance of implantation , the inner cell mass (embryo) differentiates into an outer layer called ectoderm and an inner layer called endoderm .
881- a mesoderm soon appears between the ectoderm and the endoderm .
882- these three layers give rise to all tissues (organs) in adults .
883- it needs to be mentioned here that the inner cell mass contains certain cells called stem cells which have the potency to give rise to all the tissues and organs .
884- what are the major features of embryonic development at various months of pregnancy ?
885- the human pregnancy lasts 9 months .
886- do you know for how many months pregnancy last in dogs , elephants , cats ?
887- find out .
888- in human beings , after one month of pregnancy , the embryo’s heart is formed .
889- the first sign of growing foetus may be noticed by listening to the heart sound carefully through the stethoscope .
890- by the end of the second month of pregnancy , the foetus develops limbs and digits .
891- by the end of 12 weeks (first trimester) , most of the major organ systems are formed , for example , the limbs and external genital organs are well- developed .
892- the first movements of the foetus and appearance of hair on the head are usually observed during the fifth month .
893- by the end of about 24 weeks (end of second trimester) , the body is covered with fine hair , eye-lids separate , and eyelashes are formed .
894- by the end of nine months of pregnancy , the foetus is fully developed and is ready for delivery .
895- the average duration of human pregnancy is about 9 months which is called the gestation period .
896- vigorous contraction of the uterus at the end of pregnancy causes expulsion/delivery of the foetus .
897- this process of delivery of the foetus (childbirth) is called parturition .
898- parturition is induced by a complex neuroendocrine mechanism .
899- the signals for parturition originate from the fully developed foetus and the placenta which induce mild uterine contractions called foetal ejection reflex .
900- this triggers release of oxytocin from the maternal pituitary .
901- oxytocin acts on the uterine muscle and causes stronger uterine contractions , which in turn stimulates further secretion of oxytocin .
902- the stimulatory reflex between the uterine contraction and oxytocin secretion continues resulting in stronger and stronger contractions .
903- this leads to expulsion of the baby out of the uterus through the birth canal – parturition .
904- soon after the infant is delivered , the placenta is also expelled out of the uterus .
905- what do you think the doctors inject to induce delivery ?
906- the mammary glands of the female undergo differentiation during pregnancy and starts producing milk towards the end of pregnancy by the process called lactation .
907- this helps the mother in feeding the new- born .
908- the milk produced during the initial few days of lactation is called colostrum which contains several antibodies absolutely essential to develop resistance for the new-born babies .
909- breast-feeding during the initial period of infant growth is recommended by doctors for bringing up a healthy baby .
910- humans are sexually reproducing and viviparous .
911- the male reproductive system is composed of a pair of testes , the male sex accessory ducts and the accessory glands and external genitalia .
912- each testis has about 250 compartments called testicular lobules , and each lobule contains one to three highly coiled seminiferous tubules .
913- each seminiferous tubule is lined inside by spermatogonia and sertoli cells .
914- the spermatogonia undergo meiotic divisions leading to sperm formation , while sertoli cells provide nutrition to the dividing germ cells .
915- the leydig cells outside the seminiferous tubules , synthesise and secrete testicular hormones called androgens .
916- the male external genitalia is called penis .
917- the female reproductive system consists of a pair of ovaries , a pair of oviducts , a uterus , a vagina , external genitalia , and a pair of mammary glands .
918- the ovaries produce the female gamete (ovum) and some steroid hormones (ovarian hormones) .
919- ovarian follicles in different stages of development are embedded in the stroma .
920- the oviducts , uterus and vagina are female accessory ducts .
921- the uterus has three layers namely perimetrium , myometrium and endometrium .
922- the female external genitalia includes mons pubis , labia majora , labia minora , hymen and clitoris .
923- the mammary glands are one of the female secondary sexual characteristics .
924- spermatogenesis results in the formation of sperms that are transported by the male sex accessory ducts .
925- a normal human sperm is composed of a head , neck , a middle piece and tail .
926- the process of formation of mature female gametes is called oogenesis .
927- the reproductive cycle of female primates is called menstrual cycle .
928- menstrual cycle starts only after attaining sexual maturation (puberty) .
929- during ovulation only one ovum is released per menstrual cycle .
930- the cyclical changes in the ovary and the uterus during menstrual cycle are induced by changes in the levels of pituitary and ovarian hormones .
931- after coitus , sperms are transported to the junction of the isthmus and ampulla , where the sperm fertilises the ovum leading to formation of a diploid zygote .
932- the presence of x or y chromosome in the sperm determines the sex of the embryo .
933- the zygote undergoes repeated mitotic division to form a blastocyst , which is implanted in the uterus resulting in pregnancy .
934- after nine months of pregnancy , the fully developed foetus is ready for delivery .
935- the process of childbirth is called parturition which is induced by a complex neuroendocrine mechanism involving cortisol , estrogens and oxytocin .
936- mammary glands differentiate during pregnancy and secrete milk after child-birth .
937- the new-born baby is fed milk by the mother (lactation) during the initial few months of growth .
